Romania: Renewable Energy Investments impact on Electricity Prices

Flavius Mihai Bendres

2025-04-21

Introduction

This project analyzes the impact of renewable energy investments on the electricity prices in Romania by analysing the dual-mandate approach under the integrated national climate energy plan (NECP) under the two proposed scenarios. With additional measures (WAM), and With existing measures (WEM)

To what extent does Romania’s renewable energy investments influence energy prices under the NECP’s WAM (With Additional Measures) and WEM (With Existing Measures) scenarios?

Supporting research questions include:

1. What are the implications of achieving or failing to meet Romania’s RES targets, as outlined in the NECP?

2. Are there any differences between the projected impacts of EU ETS carbon prices and Green Certificates on energy prices in Romania’s electricity generation sector, as outlined in the NECP?

3. How do the NECP’s WAM and WEM scenarios differ in their projected impacts on energy prices, particularly in the context of renewable energy investments and carbon pricing mechanisms?

Function to check duplicates

This is important especially when we’re aiming to merge the datasets to avoid the “many-to-many” relationship

check_duplicates <- function(df, name) {
  dupes <- df %>%
    group_by(Date) %>%
    summarise(n = n()) %>%
    filter(n > 1)
  if (nrow(dupes) > 0) {
    message(paste0("Duplicates in ", name, ":"))
    print(dupes)
  }
}

The “Total” line highlights general trends of the dataset by combining all the years (or groups) together. It is a useful way for the reader to see the overarching patterns without the need of concentrating on the individual groups. It gives the possibility of making a direct comparison between statistics for individual groups that are, for example, given on a yearly basis, and the statistics for the whole dataset. In this way, it draws the attention to the deviations, anomalies, or the consistency in the data.

Data Exploration Graphs

Joining the datasets

combined_data <- carbon_price %>%
  left_join(electricity_price, by = "Date") %>%
  left_join(mes_data, by = "Date") %>%
  left_join(gas_price, by = "Date") %>% 
  #left_join(demand, by = "Date") %>% 
  #left_join(imp_exp, by = "Date") %>% 
  left_join(green_certificates, by = "Date") %>% 
  mutate(Period = "Historical", Scenario = "Actual") %>%
  filter(Date <= as.Date("2022-02-28"))

emission_factors <- list(
  Coal = 334,
  NaturalGas = 205,
  biomass = 19
)

full_data <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(
    FossilFuel_Production = FossilFuel_Production - `Oil and Petroleum Products`,
    Carbon_Cost_Coal = Coal_Production * emission_factors$Coal * Carbon_Price,
    Carbon_Cost_NaturalGas = NaturalGas_Production * emission_factors$NaturalGas * Carbon_Price,
    #Carbon_Cost_CrudeOil = CrudeOil_Production * emission_factors$CrudeOil * Carbon_Price,
    Carbon_Cost_biomass = Biomass * emission_factors$biomass * Carbon_Price,
    
    # Total carbon cost (€/GWh)
    Total_Carbon_Cost = (Carbon_Cost_Coal + Carbon_Cost_NaturalGas + Carbon_Cost_biomass) / FossilFuel_Production,
    
    # Handle division by zero (if fossil fuel production is 0)
    Total_Carbon_Cost = ifelse(FossilFuel_Production == 0, 0, Total_Carbon_Cost)
  )

historical_data <- full_data

# log-transformed dependent variable
full_data <- full_data %>%
  mutate(log_Electricity_Price = log(Electricity_Price))
historical_data <- historical_data %>%
  mutate(log_Electricity_Price = log(Electricity_Price))

We can see high multicolinearity between the Total Carbon and Weight AVG so why not solve this issue first? - It’s generally more logical to determine the appropriate timeframe before you start comparing different model specifications or variable choices. - Including or excluding certain years can significantly affect the model’s coefficients and performance metrics. - Deciding on the appropriate timeframe first, we ensure that the subsequent variable selection is based on a consistent and well-defined dataset.

Sensitivity Analysis

This will allow us to determine which variable (Carbon Price or Green Certificates) is a better predictor of electricity prices within the chosen timeframe (2015-February 2022).

Separate Historical and Projection Datasets: - One for historical data (2015–2024) with variables like energy prices, carbon prices, etc. - A second dataset for projected data (2025–2050) containing RES investments under WEM and WAM scenarios and fossil fuel production projections.

Empirical Relationship between EU ETS and Green Certificates

Carbon_Price (EU ETS): This represents the cost of emitting CO2, a key driver of electricity prices, especially for fossil-fuel-based generation. Weighted_Avg_Price_PCBCV (Green Certificates): This reflects the price of certificates that demonstrate electricity has been generated from renewable sources.

There’s an inter-dependency between these two economic mechanism that have caused our regression model to exhibit multicollinearity between the Total_Carbon_Cost and Weighted_Avg_Price_PCBCV variables, as both reflect overlapping policy pressures on electricity prices. The Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) analysis of our baseline log-transformed model indicates that Total_Carbon_Cost has a VIF of 12.95, while Weighted_Avg_Price_PCBCV has a VIF of 6.47.

calculate_metrics <- function(actual_log, predicted_log, actual_original) {
  # Metrics on log scale
  mse_log <- mean((actual_log - predicted_log)^2, na.rm = TRUE)
  rmse_log <- sqrt(mse_log)
  mae_log <- mean(abs(actual_log - predicted_log), na.rm = TRUE)
  r2_log <- cor(actual_log, predicted_log, use = "complete.obs")^2

  # Back-transform predictions to original scale
  predicted_original <- exp(predicted_log)

  # Metrics on original scale
  mse_original <- mean((actual_original - predicted_original)^2, na.rm = TRUE)
  rmse_original <- sqrt(mse_original)
  mae_original <- mean(abs(actual_original - predicted_original), na.rm = TRUE)
  r2_original <- cor(actual_original, predicted_original, use = "complete.obs")^2

  return(data.frame(
    MSE_log = mse_log, RMSE_log = rmse_log, MAE_log = mae_log, R_squared_log = r2_log,
    MSE_original = mse_original, RMSE_original = rmse_original, MAE_original = mae_original, R_squared_original = r2_original
  ))
}

metrics_carbon_only <- calculate_metrics(holdout_data$log_Electricity_Price, predictions_log_carbon_only, holdout_data$Electricity_Price)
metrics_green_cert_only <- calculate_metrics(holdout_data$log_Electricity_Price, predictions_log_green_cert_only, holdout_data$Electricity_Price)
metrics_both <- calculate_metrics(holdout_data$log_Electricity_Price, predictions_log_both, holdout_data$Electricity_Price)

Why log-model and not a linear model? -> Log is considered more theoretically appropriate for modeling prices, as it captures proportional effects and ensures positive predicted prices.

The journey to our final log-linear model involved a process of iterative refinement, driven by both theoretical considerations and empirical evidence. We addressed multicollinearity, improved model assumptions through log transformation, and conducted sensitivity analyses to validate our choices. This rigorous approach has resulted in a robust and reliable model for predicting electricity prices in the Romanian market.

In the following section we will address our model-comparison and refinement to justify our decision. We believe that using the same log-model that we will use to predict electricity prices in our sensitivity analysis part showcases a good logical structure and a more reliable interpretation of the results and variable selection.

Comparing the models

AIC (Akaike Information Criterion): AIC measures the goodness of fit of a model while penalizing for the number of parameters. Lower AIC values indicate a better model.

BIC (Bayesian Information Criterion): BIC is similar to AIC but includes a stronger penalty for the number of parameters. Lower BIC values also indicate a better model.

## [1] "Baseline Model AIC: 688.934511911447"
## [1] "Baseline Model BIC: 713.477984873982"
## [1] "Log-Linear Model AIC: -42.514001929445"
## [1] "Log-Linear Model BIC: -17.9705289669099"

Interpretation AIC: The log-linear model has a significantly lower AIC (-39.50) compared to the baseline model (688.93). This indicates that the log-linear model provides a better fit to the data while using fewer parameters.

BIC: Similarly, the log-linear model has a lower BIC (-10.05) compared to the baseline model (713.48). This further supports the conclusion that the log-linear model is preferable.

Thus, this reinforces out initial assumptions that using the log-model will be a better fit for our analysis. However, the log-linear model violates the assumption of no autocorrelation, which needs to be addressed.

# The Newey-West method addresses autocorrelation by adjusting the standard errors to account for the correlation between residuals at different time points. This means that even if the residuals are not independent (which is the case with autocorrelation), the standard errors will still be reliable.

# The Newey-West procedure only affects the standard errors and the associated test statistics and p-values. The estimated regression coefficients themselves remain the same as in the standard OLS output.

Projection Data Part using the WEM and WAM scenarios

We initialize and merge the WEM and WAM scenario data, including RES and fossil fuel production, to simulate total electricity supply and RES share over time.

Then, we interpolate monthly gas and carbon prices (2025–2030) based on external expert projections to reflect realistic market conditions in each scenario.

Using emission factors, we compute carbon costs for each fossil source (coal, gas, biomass) and derive a scenario-specific Total_Carbon_Cost per GWh. ## Initializing the data sets

res_capacity_wem$Date <- as.Date(res_capacity_wem$Date)
fossil_fuel_wem$Date <- as.Date(fossil_fuel_wem$Date)

res_capacity_wam$Date <- as.Date(res_capacity_wam$Date)
fossil_fuel_wam$Date <- as.Date(fossil_fuel_wam$Date)


fossil_fuel_wem <- fossil_fuel_wem %>%
  mutate(Scenario = "WEM") 

res_capacity_wem <- res_capacity_wem %>%
  mutate(Scenario = "WEM") 

fossil_fuel_wam <- fossil_fuel_wam %>%
  mutate(Scenario = "WAM")  

res_capacity_wam <- res_capacity_wam %>%
  mutate(Scenario = "WAM")  

# 1.left_join separately for WEM
joined_data_wem <- res_capacity_wem %>%
  left_join(fossil_fuel_wem, by = c("Date", "Scenario"))

projection_wem <- joined_data_wem %>% # Start with the joined data
  mutate(Total_Electricity = `Total RES generation (GWh)` + `Total Production Fossil Fuels (Gwh)` + `Nuclear`, 
         RES_Share = (`Total RES generation (GWh)` / Total_Electricity) * 100)

# 2.left_join separately for WAM
joined_data_wam <- res_capacity_wam %>%
  left_join(fossil_fuel_wam, by = c("Date", "Scenario"))

projection_wam <- joined_data_wam %>%
  mutate(Total_Electricity = `Total RES generation (GWh)` + `Total Production Fossil Fuels (Gwh)` + `Nuclear`,
         RES_Share = (`Total RES generation (GWh)` / Total_Electricity) * 100)


# Combine both scenarios into one dataset
total_production <- bind_rows(projection_wem, projection_wam) %>%
  arrange(Date, Scenario)



# Calculate midpoint gas prices for monthly projections based on (RPIA, 2023) and (Diallo et al., 2024)
gas_prices <- data.frame(
  Date = as.Date(c("2025-01-01", "2030-12-01")),
  Price_REF = c(36, 30) * 1000,        # Convert EUR/MWh to EUR/GWh
  Price_LowGas = c(35, 29) * 1000      # Convert EUR/MWh to EUR/GWh
)

# Generate monthly dates and calculate midpoints
monthly_dates <- seq(from = as.Date("2025-01-01"), to = as.Date("2030-12-01"), by = "month")
approx_prices <- data.frame(
  Date = monthly_dates,
  Midpoint_GasPrice = approx(gas_prices$Date, 
                             (gas_prices$Price_REF + gas_prices$Price_LowGas) / 2, 
                             xout = monthly_dates)$y
)

# Merging the scenarios with the projected gas prices
total_production <- total_production %>%
  left_join(approx_prices, by = "Date") %>% 
  filter(Date <= as.Date("2030-12-01")) %>%
  arrange(Date, Scenario)


# EU ETS prices based on online sources #

# Known carbon prices for 2025 and 2030 (Dimitrova, 2024) - (Gabin et al., 2023)
known_carbon_prices <- data.frame(
  Date = as.Date(c("2025-01-01", "2030-12-01")),
  Carbon_Price = c(75, 140)  # Midpoint of 2025 and 2030 ranges
)

# Homaio’s expert consensus captures upside risks from supply tightening and financialization. For academic purposes, a midpoint estimate of €75/tCO₂ in 2025 and €140/tCO₂ in 2030 balances these perspectives, though sensitivity analyses should quantify the impact of MSR rule changes and CBAM expansion.

# Interpolate carbon prices for each date in the total_production dataset
total_production <- total_production %>%
  mutate(Carbon_Price = approx(
    x = known_carbon_prices$Date,
    y = known_carbon_prices$Carbon_Price,
    xout = as.numeric(as.Date(Date))
  )$y)

We apply the validated log-linear model to forecast electricity prices under WEM and WAM, transforming predictions back to €/MWh for interpretation.

WEM Scenario

# emission factors (t CO2/GWh) based on the NECP Electricity generation capacity (projected)
emission_factors_projected <- list(
  Coal = 334,
  NaturalGas = 205,
  biomass = 19
)

# Separate data by scenario *before* adding exogenous variables

projection_wem_final <- total_production %>%
  filter(Scenario == "WEM") %>%
  mutate(
    GasPrice = Midpoint_GasPrice,
    FossilFuel_Production = `Total Production Fossil Fuels (Gwh)`,
    Carbon_Cost_Coal = `Coal (GWh)` * emission_factors_projected$Coal * Carbon_Price,
    Carbon_Cost_NaturalGas = `NaturalGas (GWh)` * emission_factors_projected$NaturalGas * Carbon_Price,
    Carbon_Cost_biomass = `Biomass` * emission_factors$biomass * Carbon_Price,
    # Total carbon cost (€/GWh)
    Total_Carbon_Cost = (Carbon_Cost_Coal + Carbon_Cost_NaturalGas + Carbon_Cost_biomass) / FossilFuel_Production,
    #  + Carbon_Cost_NaturalGasCHP
    # get the carbon cost per GWh of fossil fuel electricity
    
    # Handle division by zero (if fossil fuel production is 0)
    Total_Carbon_Cost = ifelse(FossilFuel_Production == 0, 0, Total_Carbon_Cost),
    RES_Capacity_WEM = `Total RES generation (GWh)`
    ) %>%
  arrange(Date)


# Predictions Using the Log-Model
Projection_WEM_Final_Log <- projection_wem_final %>%
  mutate(Predicted_Log_Electricity_Price_WEM = predict(log_model, newdata = .),
         Predicted_Electricity_Price_WEM = exp(Predicted_Log_Electricity_Price_WEM)  # Converting back to original scale
        )

WAM Scenario

projection_wam_final <- total_production %>%
  filter(Scenario == "WAM") %>%
  mutate(
    GasPrice = Midpoint_GasPrice,
    FossilFuel_Production = `Total Production Fossil Fuels (Gwh)`,
    Carbon_Cost_Coal = `Coal (GWh)` * emission_factors_projected$Coal * Carbon_Price,
    Carbon_Cost_NaturalGas = `NaturalGas (GWh)` * emission_factors_projected$NaturalGas * Carbon_Price,
    # Carbon_Cost_NaturalGasCHP = `NaturalGas CHP (GWh)` * emission_factors_projected$NaturalGasCHP * Carbon_Price,
    Carbon_Cost_biomass = `Biomass` * emission_factors$biomass * Carbon_Price,
    # Total carbon cost (€/GWh)
    Total_Carbon_Cost = (Carbon_Cost_Coal + Carbon_Cost_NaturalGas + Carbon_Cost_biomass) / FossilFuel_Production,
    #  + Carbon_Cost_NaturalGasCHP
    # get the carbon cost per GWh of fossil fuel electricity
    
    # handle division by zero (if fossil fuel production is 0)
    Total_Carbon_Cost = ifelse(FossilFuel_Production == 0, 0, Total_Carbon_Cost),
    RES_Capacity_WAM = `Total RES generation (GWh)`
    ) %>%
  arrange(Date)


Projection_WAM_Final_Log <- projection_wam_final %>%
  mutate(Predicted_Log_Electricity_Price_WAM = predict(log_model, newdata = .),
         Predicted_Electricity_Price_WAM = exp(Predicted_Log_Electricity_Price_WAM))

              left_join(Projection_WAM_Final_Log %>% 
  select(Date, Predicted_Electricity_Price_WAM), by = "Date")

#----------- 2030 Log model Price Decomp --------------#

calculate_price_drivers <- function(wam_data, wem_data, wam_model, wem_model, wam_log_model, wem_log_model) {
  wam_2030 <- wam_data %>% filter(format(Date, "%Y") == "2030")
  wem_2030 <- wem_data %>% filter(format(Date, "%Y") == "2030")
  
  # differences in key variables (break down RES)
  differences <- data.frame(
    Variable = c("Total_Carbon_Cost", "GasPrice", "Wind", "Solar", "Hydro", "Biomass", "FossilFuel_Production", "Nuclear"),
    WAM_value = c(
      mean(wam_2030$Total_Carbon_Cost),
      mean(wam_2030$GasPrice),
      mean(wam_2030$Wind),
      mean(wam_2030$Solar),
      mean(wam_2030$Hydro),
      mean(wam_2030$Biomass),
      mean(wam_2030$FossilFuel_Production),
      mean(wam_2030$Nuclear)
    ),
    WEM_value = c(
      mean(wem_2030$Total_Carbon_Cost),
      mean(wem_2030$GasPrice),
      mean(wem_2030$Wind),
      mean(wem_2030$Solar),
      mean(wem_2030$Hydro),
      mean(wem_2030$Biomass),
      mean(wem_2030$FossilFuel_Production),
      mean(wem_2030$Nuclear)
    )
  )
  
  differences$Absolute_Difference <- differences$WAM_value - differences$WEM_value
  
  # Get coefficients and transform log coefficients
  wam_coef <- coef(wam_model)
  wem_coef <- coef(wem_model)
  wam_log_coef <- coef(wam_log_model)
  wem_log_coef <- coef(wem_log_model)
  
  # Function to transform log coefficient
  transform_log_coef <- function(coef) {
    (exp(coef) - 1) * mean(wem_2030$Predicted_Electricity_Price_WEM) # Use WEM mean price
  }
  
  # average coefficients (transformed for log model)
  differences$Average_Coefficient <- c(
    mean(c(wam_coef["Total_Carbon_Cost"], wem_coef["Total_Carbon_Cost"])),
    mean(c(wam_coef["GasPrice"], wem_coef["GasPrice"])),
    mean(c(transform_log_coef(wam_log_coef["Wind"]), transform_log_coef(wem_log_coef["Wind"]))),
    mean(c(transform_log_coef(wam_log_coef["Solar"]), transform_log_coef(wem_log_coef["Solar"]))),
    mean(c(transform_log_coef(wam_log_coef["Hydro"]), transform_log_coef(wem_log_coef["Hydro"]))),
    mean(c(transform_log_coef(wam_log_coef["Biomass"]), transform_log_coef(wem_log_coef["Biomass"]))),
    mean(c(wam_coef["FossilFuel_Production"], wem_coef["FossilFuel_Production"])),
    mean(c(wam_coef["Nuclear"], wem_coef["Nuclear"]))
  )
  
  # price impact
  differences$Price_Impact_Linear <- differences$Absolute_Difference * differences$Average_Coefficient
  
  differences$Price_Impact_Log <- (exp(differences$Average_Coefficient * differences$Absolute_Difference) - 1) *     
    mean(wem_2030$Predicted_Electricity_Price_WEM)
  
  
  return(differences %>% arrange(desc(abs(Price_Impact_Linear)))) # You can sort by either linear or log impact
}


price_drivers <- calculate_price_drivers(
  Projection_WAM_Final_Log,  
  Projection_WEM_Final_Log,   
  baseline_model,             
  baseline_model,             
  log_model,               
  log_model                 
)

Alternative models

Generalized least squares to address multicolinearrity

(GLS) is a method used to estimate the unknown parameters in a linear regression model. It is used when there is a non-zero amount of correlation between the residuals in the regression model.

# Fit a GLS model with AR(1) correlation structure
gls_model <- gls(log_Electricity_Price ~ Total_Carbon_Cost + GasPrice + Wind + Solar + 
                Hydro + Biomass + FossilFuel_Production + Nuclear, 
                data = full_data,
                correlation = corAR1(form = ~1))
# even though GasPrice and Total_Carbon_Cost are moderately correlated it does not introduce multicolinearrity.

ARIMA implementation

# Load necessary libraries
library(forecast)
library(tseries)

# Ensure the data is stationary
electricity_prices <- full_data$log_Electricity_Price
stationary_test <- adf.test(electricity_prices)
print(stationary_test)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  electricity_prices
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.5234, Lag order = 4, p-value = 0.7717
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
#initially, not stationary - fail to reject H0

# If the data is not stationary, apply differencing
if (stationary_test$p.value > 0.05) {
  electricity_prices <- diff(electricity_prices)
}

stationary_test_after_diff <- adf.test(electricity_prices)
print(stationary_test_after_diff)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  electricity_prices
## Dickey-Fuller = -4.5251, Lag order = 4, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
# the data is stationary now


# Plot ACF and PACF
# 𝑝(autoregressive term) and q (moving average term)
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
acf(electricity_prices, main = "ACF of Electricity Prices") #The ACF measures the correlation of the time series with its own lagged values.
pacf(electricity_prices, main = "PACF of Electricity Prices") # PACF measures the correlation of the time series with its own lagged values after removing the effects of earlier lags.

#significant spike at lag 1 which suggests a potential value for q=1 in the moving average (MA) component.
# significant spike at lag 1 suggests a potential value for p=1 in the autoregressive (AR) component.

# Fit the ARIMA model
arima_model <- auto.arima(full_data$log_Electricity_Price)
summary(arima_model)

What can we see from this implementation? ARIMA(2,0,2): The model includes two autoregressive terms (AR) and two moving average terms (MA), with no differencing (𝑑=0).

Coefficients:

AR1 = -0.7544, AR2 = -0.6690 MA1 = 0.9658, MA2 = 0.5019

These coefficients represent the weights assigned to lagged observations and errors, and their statistical significance suggests the model is well-fitted to the data. The standard errors (s.e.) are reasonably small, further supporting the reliability of the coefficients.

Error Variance 0.03177. This indicates the variability of the residuals is low, which is desirable for a good-fitting model.

Information Criteria: AIC = -45.49, BIC = -33.28. Lower values of AIC and BIC indicate a better-fitting model.

  • The Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE = 0.17398) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE = 0.13731) indicate the model’s predictive accuracy on the training set. These values are relatively low, suggesting that the model performs well in fitting the data.

Residual Diagnostics:

  • Ljung-Box Test: p-value = 0.5208: This indicates that the residuals do not exhibit significant autocorrelation. The null hypothesis (residuals are white noise) cannot be rejected.

  • The Box-Ljung test confirms no significant autocorrelation, further validating the adequacy of the model.

Residual Graphs:

  • The residuals fluctuate around zero without evident patterns, supporting the assumption of white noise.

  • The autocorrelations are within the confidence bounds, reinforcing the absence of autocorrelation.

  • The residuals closely follow a normal distribution, as seen in the histogram overlaid with a normal curve. This supports the assumption of normally distributed residuals

# Emission factors (t CO2/GWh) based on the NECP Electricity generation capacity (projected)
emission_factors_projected <- list(
  Coal = 334,
  NaturalGas = 205,
  biomass = 19
)

# Separate data by scenario *before* adding exogenous variables
projection_wem_final <- total_production %>%
  filter(Scenario == "WEM") %>%
  mutate(
    FossilFuel_Production = `Total Production Fossil Fuels (Gwh)`,
    Carbon_Cost_Coal = `Coal (GWh)` * emission_factors_projected$Coal * Carbon_Price,
    Carbon_Cost_NaturalGas = `NaturalGas (GWh)` * emission_factors_projected$NaturalGas * Carbon_Price,
    Carbon_Cost_biomass = `Biomass` * emission_factors_projected$biomass * Carbon_Price,
    # Total carbon cost (€/GWh)
    Total_Carbon_Cost = (Carbon_Cost_Coal + Carbon_Cost_NaturalGas + Carbon_Cost_biomass) / FossilFuel_Production,
    # Handle division by zero (if fossil fuel production is 0)
    Total_Carbon_Cost = ifelse(FossilFuel_Production == 0, 0, Total_Carbon_Cost),
    RES_Capacity_WEM = `Total RES generation (GWh)`
  ) %>%
  arrange(Date)

# Forecast using the ARIMA model

  mutate(Predicted_Log_Electricity_Price_WEM = forecast(arima_model, h = length(projection_wem_final$Date))$mean,
         Predicted_Electricity_Price_WEM = exp(Predicted_Log_Electricity_Price_WEM))  # Converting back to original scale
